    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Home-Grown Talent</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Frances R Curcio letter on June 26 article holds New York City and New York State should invest in infrastructure that attracts best prepared math and science teachers, not rely on importing teachers from foreign nations</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Although importing math and science teachers from foreign countries may be a commendable quick fix to New York City's teacher shortage (news article, June 26), New York City and New York State need to invest in building an infrastructure that attracts the best prepared, best qualified and most committed professionals from our own schools.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Although importing math and science teachers from foreign countries may be a commendable quick fix to New York City's teacher shortage (news article, June 26), New York City and New York State need to invest in building an infrastructure that attracts the best prepared, best qualified and most committed professionals from our own schools.</p>
        <p>Imported teachers may find that being ''mean'' and relying on a ''chalk and talk'' lecture approach helps them to survive temporarily, but what long-term measures are being taken to improve the teaching and learning of mathematics and science in our schools?</p>
        <p>We need more than a Band-Aid treatment for a situation that requires major surgery.</p>
        <p>FRANCES R. CURCIO  New York, June 26, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of mathematics education at N.Y.U.</p>
      </block>
